Naomi Elaine Campbell, born on 22 May 1970, is a British model whose career is less a timeline and more a tectonic shift in the landscape of modern culture. She began her ascent at the tender age of eight, a prelude to becoming one of the six models of her era anointed as "[supermodels](/Supermodel)" by a fawning [fashion industry](/Fashion_industry) and an equally captivated international press. Her presence was a declaration, marking her as the first black woman to stare out from the covers of [Time](/Time_(magazine)) and, pivotally, [Vogue France](/Vogue_France).

Beyond the relentless flash of the camera, Campbell has ventured into other arenas with varying degrees of success. Her explorations include a foray into music with [an R&B studio album](/Babywoman) and a collection of acting appearances in film and television. She later took on the role of host for the modeling competition reality series [The Face](/The_Face_(TV_series)) and its global offshoots, proving she could cultivate talent as well as embody it. Campbell has also been deeply involved in charity work, a pursuit that recently culminated in a five-year ban from serving as a trustee for any UK charity. A misconduct investigation in September 2024 revealed that her charity directed a mere 8.5% of its income toward actual charitable grants, while the rest funded... other priorities. These included Campbell's stay at a five-star hotel, spa treatments, room service, security, and, poetically, cigarettes.

### Early life

Naomi Elaine Campbell was delivered into the world on 22 May 1970 in [Lambeth](/Lambeth), South London, the daughter of Valerie Morris, a dancer of Jamaican origin. In a decision that would shape her narrative, Campbell has, at her mother's request, never met the man who fathered her. He absconded when her mother was four months pregnant and remains a nameless omission on her birth certificate. The surname "Campbell" was adopted from her mother's second marriage. A half-brother, Pierre, arrived in 1985. Campbell's heritage is a rich tapestry of Black-Jamaican and Chinese-Jamaican ancestry, the latter inherited from her maternal grandmother, whose family name was Ming.

Her formative years were spent not in London, but in [Rome](/Rome), Italy, where her mother was employed as a [modern dancer](/Modern_dance). Upon their return to London, she was placed in the care of relatives as her mother toured Europe with the dance troupe Fantastica. Campbell's training for the stage began early; from the age of three, she was a student at the [Barbara Speake Stage School](/Barbara_Speake_Stage_School). By ten, her talent secured her a place at the prestigious [Italia Conti Academy of Theatre Arts](/Italia_Conti_Academy_of_Theatre_Arts), where she immersed herself in the study of [ballet](/Ballet). Her education also included attendance at [Dunraven School](/Dunraven_School).

### Career

#### 1978–1986: Career beginnings

Campbell’s first brush with the public eye occurred in 1978. At eight years old, she appeared in the music video for [Bob Marley](/Bob_Marley)'s iconic song "[Is This Love](/Is_This_Love_(Bob_Marley_song))", filmed at the Keskidee Centre, a pioneering Black-led arts venue in London. Her rhythm found other outlets; she was seen tap-dancing in the 1983 music video for [Culture Club](/Culture_Club)'s "[I'll Tumble 4 Ya](/I%27ll_Tumble_4_Ya)" and again for "Mistake No. 3" in 1984. Having studied dance from age three to sixteen, her original ambition was to be a dancer, not a model. Fate, however, had a less choreographed plan. In 1986, while still a student at the Italia Conti Academy of Theatre Arts, she was discovered by Beth Boldt, the head of the Synchro Model Agency. The setting was not a casting call, but a simple window-shopping excursion in [Covent Garden](/Covent_Garden). Her ascent was immediate. In April, just shy of her 16th birthday, she was on the cover of British [Elle](/Elle_(magazine)).

#### 1987–1997: Supermodel status

The years that followed cemented her legacy. Campbell became a fixture on the catwalks for designers who defined the era: [Gianni Versace](/Gianni_Versace), [Azzedine Alaïa](/Azzedine_Ala%C3%AFa), and [Isaac Mizrahi](/Isaac_Mizrahi). Her image was immortalized by photographers like [Peter Lindbergh](/Peter_Lindbergh), [Herb Ritts](/Herb_Ritts), and [Bruce Weber](/Bruce_Weber_(photographer)). By the late 1980s, Campbell, alongside [Christy Turlington](/Christy_Turlington) and [Linda Evangelista](/Linda_Evangelista), formed a formidable trio known as the "Trinity." They were not just models; they were the faces of a generation, the most recognizable and sought-after figures in fashion.

When confronted with the industry's pervasive [racial discrimination](/Racial_discrimination), Campbell found unwavering support from her white peers. She famously recalled Turlington and Evangelista issuing an ultimatum to [Dolce & Gabbana](/Dolce_%26_Gabbana): "If you don't use Naomi, you don't get us." In December 1987, she broke a significant barrier by appearing on the cover of British [Vogue](/Vogue_(British_magazine)), the first black cover model for the publication since 1966. Another milestone followed in August 1988, when she became the first black model to grace the cover of French [Vogue](/Vogue_Paris). This was not an act of sudden enlightenment by the magazine, but the result of her friend and mentor, designer [Yves St. Laurent](/Yves_Saint_Laurent_(designer)), threatening to pull all his advertising if they refused to feature her. The next year, she conquered American [Vogue](/Vogue_(magazine)), her cover for the September issue marking the first time a black model had fronted the magazine's largest and most important edition of the year.

In January 1990, [Interview](/Interview_(magazine)) magazine declared her "the reigning megamodel of them all." She appeared on a now-legendary British Vogue cover shot by Peter Lindbergh, alongside Turlington, Evangelista, [Cindy Crawford](/Cindy_Crawford), and [Tatjana Patitz](/Tatjana_Patitz). This group was promptly cast in [George Michael](/George_Michael)'s music video for "[Freedom! '90](/Freedom!_%2790)", a cultural touchstone that solidified their status. By this point, the term "[supermodels](/Supermodel)" was coined for Campbell, Turlington, Evangelista, Crawford, and [Claudia Schiffer](/Claudia_Schiffer). With the later addition of [Kate Moss](/Kate_Moss), they became known as the "Big Six".

In March 1991, in a moment of pure fashion theatre, Campbell walked the [Versace](/Versace) runway with Turlington, Evangelista, and Crawford, arm-in-arm, lip-synching the lyrics to "Freedom! '90". Her magnetic presence extended beyond the catwalk. In March 1992, she was cast as [Michael Jackson](/Michael_Jackson)'s love interest in the cinematic music video for "[In the Closet](/In_the_Closet)". That April, she was part of the ensemble of top models photographed by [Patrick Demarchelier](/Patrick_Demarchelier) for the hundredth-anniversary cover of American Vogue. The same year, she appeared in [Madonna](/Madonna)'s provocative book [Sex](/Sex_(book)), featured in a series of nude photographs with Madonna and rapper [Big Daddy Kane](/Big_Daddy_Kane).

The year 1993 saw Campbell on the cover of American Vogue twice: once in April with a supermodel cohort including Christy Turlington, Claudia Schiffer, [Stephanie Seymour](/Stephanie_Seymour), and [Helena Christensen](/Helena_Christensen), and again solo in June. It was also the year of her famous tumble on the Vivienne Westwood Fall 1993 catwalk, where she navigated foot-high [platform shoes](/Platform_shoes) with more drama than grace. The shoes, now artifacts, were later exhibited at the [Victoria and Albert Museum](/Victoria_and_Albert_Museum) in London. Despite her soaring success, her relationship with [Elite Model Management](/Elite_Model_Management), her agency since 1987, fractured, and they dropped her from their roster.

In 1996, Campbell walked in the second-ever Victoria's Secret Fashion Show, making history as the first black model to open the spectacle. She would walk for the brand seven times, her final appearance in 2005. When asked why she never became a contracted Angel, her response was characteristically blunt: "[They] could not afford me". Another barrier fell in 1997, when she became the first black woman to open a [Prada](/Prada) show.

The mid-1990s saw Campbell dabble in other entertainment ventures. Her novel, *Swan*, a tale of a supermodel ensnared in blackmail, was released in 1994. It was [ghostwritten](/Ghostwriter) by Caroline Upcher, a fact Campbell didn't hide, stating she "just did not have the time to sit down and write a book." That same year, she released her album [Babywoman](/Babywoman), titled after a nickname given to her by designer [Rifat Ozbek](/Rifat_Ozbek). Produced by [Youth](/Martin_Glover) and [Tim Simenon](/Tim_Simenon), the album found commercial success only in Japan. Its single, "Love and Tears," peaked at No. 40 on the charts. *Babywoman* was widely derided by critics, even inspiring the creation of the [Naomi Awards](/Naomi_Awards) for bad music. During this period, she also took on small roles in films like [Miami Rhapsody](/Miami_Rhapsody) and [Spike Lee](/Spike_Lee)'s [Girl 6](/Girl_6), and had a recurring role in the second season of the television series [New York Undercover](/New_York_Undercover).

#### 1998–2012: Other ventures

In 1998, [Time](/Time_(magazine)) magazine boldly declared the end of the supermodel era. Campbell, apparently, did not receive the memo. She continued to work relentlessly, both on the runway and, more frequently, in print campaigns. In 1999, she secured her first major cosmetics contract with Cosmopolitan Cosmetics, a division of [Wella](/Wella), which launched a successful line of signature fragrances under her name. In November of that year, she joined 12 other top models for the "Modern Muses" cover of the Millennium Issue of American Vogue, shot by [Annie Leibovitz](/Annie_Leibovitz). The following month, she appeared on the cover of [Playboy](/Playboy_(magazine)) magazine, clad in a white string bikini and furs. In May 2001, she co-hosted the [50th Miss Universe pageant](/Miss_Universe_2001) alongside fellow supermodel [Elle Macpherson](/Elle_Macpherson). That October, she shared the cover of British Vogue with rapper [Sean "Puff Daddy" Combs](/Sean_Combs), under the headline "Naomi and Puff: The Ultimate Power Duo".

In 2007, she returned to the catwalk for [Dior](/Christian_Dior_S.A.)'s 60th-anniversary fashion show at the opulent Palace of [Versailles](/Versailles_(city)). A landmark moment came in July 2008, when she appeared on the gatefold cover of an all-black issue of Italian [Vogue](/Vogue_Italia), shot by [Steven Meisel](/Steven_Meisel) alongside fellow black models [Liya Kebede](/Liya_Kebede), [Sessilee Lopez](/Sessilee_Lopez), and [Jourdan Dunn](/Jourdan_Dunn). In September of that year, she reunited with the original supermodels—Christy Turlington, Linda Evangelista, Cindy Crawford, Claudia Schiffer, and Stephanie Seymour—for a [Vanity Fair](/Vanity_Fair_(magazine)) feature titled "A League of Their Own," reflecting on their enduring legacy.

In 2011, Campbell, along with Liya Kebede and [Iman](/Iman_(model)), graced the cover of the 40th-anniversary issue of [Essence](/Essence_(magazine)). She also starred in [Duran Duran](/Duran_Duran)'s music video for "Girl Panic!", brilliantly portraying frontman [Simon Le Bon](/Simon_Le_Bon), while Cindy Crawford, Helena Christensen, [Eva Herzigova](/Eva_Herzigova), and [Yasmin Le Bon](/Yasmin_Le_Bon) played the other band members. The supergroup was featured in the November edition of British [Harper's Bazaar](/Harper%27s_Bazaar) in an editorial titled "The Supers vs. Duran Duran". In a display of national pride and high fashion, Campbell joined Kate Moss and other supermodels in the closing ceremony of the [2012 Olympic Games](/2012_Olympic_Games). They modelled haute couture to represent the pinnacle of British fashion, with Campbell wearing a dramatic, gold-flecked gown by [Alexander McQueen](/Alexander_McQueen).

#### 2013–2020

In March 2013, Campbell was chosen for the inaugural cover of [Numéro](/Num%C3%A9ro) Russia. She then moved into the world of [reality television](/Reality_television), bringing her formidable presence to the modeling competition [The Face](/The_Face_(U.S._TV_series)) and its international spin-offs. In the U.S. version on [Oxygen](/Oxygen_(TV_channel)), she served as a coach and judge alongside [Karolina Kurkova](/Karolina_Kurkova) and [Coco Rocha](/Coco_Rocha), with photographer [Nigel Barker](/Nigel_Barker_(photographer)) as host. She also hosted [the British version](/The_Face_(UK_TV_series)) on [Sky Living](/Sky_Living) later that year, and [The Face Australia](/The_Face_(Australian_TV_series)), which aired on [Fox8](/Fox8) in 2014.

Her editorial dominance continued unabated. In 2014, Campbell covered the May issue of Vogue Australia, the September issue of Vogue Japan, and the November issue of Vogue Turkey, the latter two being special editions celebrating her and her fellow supermodels. She also appeared on the covers of the Vietnamese, Singaporean, and the 35th-anniversary Latin American edition of Harper's Bazaar. That same year, she was named TV Personality of the Year by Glamour Magazine at the annual Glamour Women of the Year Awards in London. The following year, she closed the Fall/Winter [Zac Posen](/Zac_Posen) show during [New York Fashion Week](/New_York_Fashion_Week) and was the face of Spring/Summer 2015 campaigns for [Burberry](/Burberry) and lingerie brand [Agent Provocateur](/Agent_Provocateur_(lingerie)).

She further expanded her acting portfolio in 2015, signing on for a recurring role in the [Fox](/Fox_Broadcasting_Company) drama [Empire](/Empire_(2015_TV_series)) as Camilla Marks, a formidable fashion designer entangled with Hakeem Lyon, played by [Bryshere Y. Gray](/Bryshere_Y._Gray). In October 2015, she appeared in a two-episode arc on [American Horror Story: Hotel](/American_Horror_Story:_Hotel) as a [Vogue](/Vogue_(magazine)) fashion editor named Claudia Bankson. In 2016, she was cast in another [Fox](/Fox_Broadcasting_Company) musical drama, [Star (TV series)](/Star_(TV_series)), playing Rose Crane, the mother of Alexandra Crane (played by [Ryan Destiny](/Ryan_Destiny)) and wife of Ronald Crane (played by [Lenny Kravitz](/Lenny_Kravitz)). She also appeared in the striking music video for [Anohni](/Anohni)'s single "[Drone Bomb Me](/Drone_Bomb_Me)".

In September 2017, she participated in a truly iconic moment at Versace's Spring/Summer 2018 show, a tribute to the late [Gianni Versace](/Gianni_Versace). She walked alongside Schiffer, Crawford, Christensen, and [Carla Bruni](/Carla_Bruni), and also featured in the collection's campaign. In February 2018, Campbell and Moss closed [Kim Jones](/Kim_Jones_(designer))' final menswear show for Louis Vuitton. In April, she shared the cover of British GQ with rapper [Skepta](/Skepta). In June 2018, the [Council of Fashion Designers of America](/Council_of_Fashion_Designers_of_America) officially recognized her indelible impact, presenting her with the Fashion Icon award. In a career of firsts, she achieved another in 2019, landing her first-ever beauty contract with [NARS Cosmetics](/NARS_Cosmetics).

In the spring of 2020, as the [COVID-19 pandemic](/COVID-19_pandemic) brought the world to a standstill, Campbell launched her own web series on [YouTube](/YouTube), *No Filter with Naomi*. The show featured candid conversations with a range of guests, starting with her old friend [Cindy Crawford](/Cindy_Crawford) and continuing with figures from [Marc Jacobs](/Marc_Jacobs) and [Adut Akech](/Adut_Akech) to [Ashley Graham](/Ashley_Graham_(model)) and [Nicole Richie](/Nicole_Richie). The 50th episode, featuring [Jean Paul Gaultier](/Jean_Paul_Gaultier), aired in March 2021. In August 2020, she partnered with [Studio71](/ProSiebenSat.1_Media) to manage her digital content, ad sales, and brand partnerships across platforms like YouTube and [Facebook](/Facebook).

#### Wikipedia page whitewashing

It came to light that the public relations firm [Sunshine Sachs](/Sunshine_Sachs), in Campbell's employ, had engaged in undisclosed paid editing of her Wikipedia page. The edits were strategically aimed at sanitizing her public image, specifically removing references to her album *Babywoman* and details about her relationship with [Mike Tyson](/Mike_Tyson). A predictable, if clumsy, attempt to curate reality.

#### 2021–present

On 12 January 2021, Campbell was named a tourism ambassador by the Kenyan Ministry of Tourism and Wildlife. In February, she appeared on the cover of [i-D](/I-D)'s spring issue and noted that it was one of the very few times in her extensive career she had worked with a [photographer](/Photographer) of colour. The following month, she was announced as the face of the relaunch [advertising campaign](/Advertising_campaign) for the influential [streetwear](/Streetwear) brand [Hood by Air](/Hood_By_Air). In July 2022, the [University for the Creative Arts](/University_for_the_Creative_Arts) (UCA) in London awarded Campbell an honorary doctorate in recognition of her profound impact on global fashion.

Campbell served as an [executive producer](/Executive_produced) on the film *Invisible Beauty*, a documentary about the pioneering model and advocate [Bethann Hardison](/Bethann_Hardison), which premiered at the [2023 Sundance Film Festival](/2023_Sundance_Film_Festival). In August 2023, Victoria's Secret unveiled its Icon Collection, featuring Campbell alongside other legends like [Gisele Bündchen](/Gisele_B%C3%BCndchen) and [Candice Swanepoel](/Candice_Swanepoel). The campaign, shot by [Mikael Jansson](/Mikael_Jansson_(photographer)), also included new faces such as [Paloma Elsesser](/Paloma_Elsesser) and [Emily Ratajkowski](/Emily_Ratajkowski). That same month, [Hugo Boss](/Hugo_Boss) launched a new collection with a campaign featuring Campbell (dubbed "Queen Boss"), [Suki Waterhouse](/Suki_Waterhouse), [Matteo Berrettini](/Matteo_Berrettini), and [Lee Min-ho](/Lee_Min-ho). On 5 September 2023, she kicked off New York Fashion Week with the debut of her collaboration with PrettyLittleThing, a collection she designed with Victor Anate and Edvin Thompson.

She is also featured in the 2023 four-part [Apple TV+](/Apple_TV%2B) [docuseries](/Television_documentary) titled [The Super Models](/The_Super_Models), alongside Cindy Crawford, Christy Turlington, and Linda Evangelista. The series is directed by [Roger Ross Williams](/Roger_Ross_Williams) and Larissa Bills. Since 2023, she has also held the role of special advisor to Gamma, the music company founded by former [Apple Music](/Apple_Music) executive Larry Jackson.

In June 2024, the [Victoria and Albert Museum](/Victoria_and_Albert_Museum) in London launched "Naomi: In Fashion," a solo exhibition dedicated to her career. The exhibit showcases around 100 curated outfits from her four decades in the industry and highlights her philanthropic work and activism.

As of 2024, her client list reads like a directory of global fashion. She has walked runways and appeared in campaigns for [Marc Jacobs](/Marc_Jacobs), [Yves Saint Laurent](/Yves_Saint_Laurent_(brand)), [Chloé](/Chlo%C3%A9), [Diane Von Furstenberg](/Diane_Von_Furstenberg), [Prada](/Prada), [Chanel](/Chanel), [Givenchy](/Givenchy), [Dolce & Gabbana](/Dolce_%26_Gabbana), [Burberry](/Burberry), [Zac Posen](/Zac_Posen), [Blumarine](/Blumarine), [Karl Lagerfeld](/Karl_Lagerfeld), [Gianfranco Ferré](/Gianfranco_Ferr%C3%A9), [Versace](/Versace), [Helmut Lang](/Helmut_Lang_(fashion_brand)), [Christian Dior](/Christian_Dior), [John Galliano](/John_Galliano), [Ralph Lauren](/Ralph_Lauren), [Jean Paul Gaultier](/Jean_Paul_Gaultier), [Tommy Hilfiger](/Tommy_Hilfiger), [Oscar de la Renta](/Oscar_de_la_Renta), [Michael Kors](/Michael_Kors), [Anna Sui](/Anna_Sui), [Louis Vuitton](/Louis_Vuitton), [Hermés](/Herm%C3%A9s), [Marchesa](/Marchesa), [Roberto Cavalli](/Roberto_Cavalli), [Valentino](/Valentino_(fashion_designer)), [Fendi](/Fendi), [Escada](/Escada), [Isaac Mizrahi](/Isaac_Mizrahi), [La Perla](/La_Perla_(lingerie_brand)), [Philipp Plein](/Philipp_Plein), [Mango](/Mango_(clothing)), [Thierry Mugler](/Thierry_Mugler), [Balmain](/Balmain_(fashion_house)), [Nars](/NARS_Cosmetics), [David Yurman](/David_Yurman), [Alessandro Dell'Acqua](/Alessandro_Dell%27Acqua), [DSquared2](/DSquared2), [Express](/Express,_Inc.), [H&M](/H%26M), [Bloomingdale's](/Bloomingdale%27s), [Dillard's](/Dillard%27s), [Neiman Marcus](/Neiman_Marcus), [Gap](/Gap_Inc.), [Avon](/Avon_Products), [Revlon](/Revlon), and [Victoria's Secret](/Victoria%27s_Secret).

### Recognition, activism and charity work

Despite her undeniable status as the most celebrated black model of her generation, Campbell consistently faced a commercial ceiling that her white colleagues did not. She was never awarded the same volume of lucrative advertising contracts and, remarkably, was not signed by a major cosmetics company until 1999. In 1991, she stated the disparity plainly: "I may be considered one of the top models in the world, but in no way do I make the same money as any of them."

Throughout her career, Campbell has been a vocal critic of the racial bias entrenched within the fashion industry. In 1997, she observed, "There is prejudice. It is a problem and I can't go along any more with brushing it under the carpet. This business is about selling, and blonde and blue-eyed girls are what sells." More than a decade later, little had changed. "The American president may be black, but as a black woman, I am still an exception in this business," she said. "I always have to work harder to be treated equally." In 2013, she joined forces with fellow models [Iman](/Iman_(model)) and [Bethann Hardison](/Bethann_Hardison) to form the "Diversity Coalition." The group issued an open letter to the governing bodies of global fashion weeks, publicly naming high-profile designers who used only one or no models of colour in their Autumn 2013 shows, condemning the practice as a "racist act."

Campbell has dedicated significant time to charitable causes. She is a supporter of the [Nelson Mandela Children's Fund](/Nelson_Mandela_Children%27s_Fund), for which she organized a benefit [Versace](/Versace) fashion show in 1998 at [Nelson Mandela](/Nelson_Mandela)'s presidential residence in South Africa. Having watched her mother battle breast cancer, she also supports [Breakthrough Breast Cancer](/Breakthrough_Breast_Cancer). In 2004, she was featured on [FHM](/FHM)'s charity single "[Da Ya Think I'm Sexy?](/Da_Ya_Think_I%27m_Sexy%3F)", with all profits donated to the cause. She has also appeared in campaigns for the charity's Fashion Targets Breast Cancer initiative and opened a new research unit for them in 2009.

In 2005, she founded We Love Brazil, a charity aimed at fighting poverty in Brazil by selling fabrics made by local women. That same year, she launched [Fashion for Relief](/Fashion_for_Relief), which organized fundraising fashion shows to benefit victims of global crises, including [Hurricane Katrina](/Hurricane_Katrina) (2005), the [Mumbai terrorist attacks](/2008_Mumbai_attacks) (2008), the [Haiti earthquake](/2010_Haiti_earthquake) (2010), the [Japan earthquake](/2011_T%C5%8Dhoku_earthquake_and_tsunami) (2011), and the [Syrian refugee crisis](/Refugees_of_the_Syrian_civil_war) (2017). By 2011, the charity had reportedly raised £4.5 million. However, following a [Charity Commission](/Charity_Commission_for_England_and_Wales) investigation that began in 2021, Campbell was removed as a [trustee](/Trustee) in 2023, and the charity was officially closed in March 2024.

In November 2010, Campbell and her then-partner [Vladislav Doronin](/Vladislav_Doronin) helped organize the Help the Tiger charity event at the [Mikhailovsky Theatre](/Mikhailovsky_Theatre) in [Saint Petersburg](/Saint_Petersburg), Russia, an event attended by figures such as [Leonardo DiCaprio](/Leonardo_DiCaprio) and [Vladimir Putin](/Vladimir_Putin). She has been the honorary president of the Italian organization Athla Onlus since 2007 and became a goodwill ambassador for the [White Ribbon Alliance for Safe Motherhood](/White_Ribbon_Alliance_for_Safe_Motherhood) in 2009, working alongside [Sarah Brown](/Sarah_Jane_Brown), wife of former British Prime Minister [Gordon Brown](/Gordon_Brown).

Her philanthropic work has earned her accolades. In 2007, Rio de Janeiro Mayor [Cesar Maia](/Cesar_Maia) named her an ambassador of the city. In 2009, she was awarded Honorary Patronage of [Trinity College](/Trinity_College,_Dublin)'s [University Philosophical Society](/University_Philosophical_Society). In 2010, British [Elle](/Elle_(magazine)) gave her an "Outstanding Contribution" award. In 2016, [amfAR](/AmfAR) honored her for three decades of work with the foundation to fund [AIDS research](/AIDS_research).

In February 2021, she was a signatory on an [open letter](/Open_letter) condemning [Ghana](/Ghana)'s stance on [gay rights](/LGBT_rights_by_country_or_territory), alongside actor [Idris Elba](/Idris_Elba) and British Vogue [editor-in-chief](/Editor-in-chief) [Edward Enninful](/Edward_Enninful). In July 2021, she publicly condemned the racist abuse directed at black players of the [England national football team](/England_national_football_team)—[Bukayo Saka](/Bukayo_Saka), [Marcus Rashford](/Marcus_Rashford), and [Jadon Sancho](/Jadon_Sancho)—following their loss in the [UEFA Euro 2020](/UEFA_Euro_2020) final. That same month, she wrote an open letter to former [South African](/South_Africa) president [Jacob Zuma](/Jacob_Zuma) regarding the [riots and unrest](/2021_South_African_unrest) that followed his incarceration.

#### Banned as charity trustee

In September 2024, the slow-motion car crash of her charity work reached its inevitable conclusion. Campbell was banned from serving as a charity trustee in the UK for five years. An investigation uncovered "multiple instances of misconduct and / or mismanagement." The inquiry found that between April 2016 and July 2022, Fashion for Relief spent a paltry 8.5% of its income on actual charitable grants. The remainder was funneled into unauthorized payments to trustees and advisors, including funding Campbell's stay at a five-star hotel in Cannes, France, along with spa treatments, room service, security, and cigarettes.

The charity first drew scrutiny after a 2019 event at the British Museum was advertised as a partnership with [UNICEF](/UNICEF). UNICEF later stated it had no knowledge of the event, was not a partner, and received no funds. Questions also arose about Campbell being described as a UNICEF "envoy" when she held no such official title. [Save the Children](/Save_the_Children) Fund and the Mayor's Fund for London also filed complaints over the charity's failure to pay them proceeds from events in 2017 and 2018. A sum of £345,000 was eventually recovered and donated to the organizations. Campbell has appealed the ban, claiming she was a "victim of fraud and forgery" and "concerted deception" by a fellow trustee, insisting she has "never undertaken philanthropic work for personal gain."

### Legal issues

Campbell has been convicted of assault on four separate occasions between 1998 and 2009. In September 1998, she was convicted of assaulting her personal assistant. In January 2007, she pleaded guilty to assaulting her former housekeeper. She served her community service in a series of designer outfits, including fedoras, furs, and a silver-sequinned $300,000 [Dolce & Gabbana](/Dolce_%26_Gabbana) gown on her final day—a masterclass in defiant glamour. She later documented the experience for a [W](/W_(magazine)) feature titled "The Naomi Diaries" and even spoofed herself in a [Dunkin' Donuts](/Dunkin%27_Donuts) commercial directed by [Zach Braff](/Zach_Braff). In June 2008, she was sentenced for assaulting two police officers at [London Heathrow Airport](/London_Heathrow_Airport). In July 2015, a court in Rome found her guilty of assaulting a [paparazzo](/Paparazzo).

### Personal life

In a 2010 interview with [British Vogue](/British_Vogue), Campbell disclosed that she had entered rehabilitation for a [cocaine](/Cocaine) addiction in 1999 and subsequently joined [Alcoholics Anonymous](/Alcoholics_Anonymous) to maintain her sobriety. She reportedly stopped drinking entirely around 2012.

#### Family and relationships

Campbell has never met her biological father. She considered the late French-Tunisian fashion designer [Azzedine Alaïa](/Azzedine_Ala%C3%AFa), whom she met at 16, to be her "papa." She also regards record producers [Quincy Jones](/Quincy_Jones) and [Chris Blackwell](/Chris_Blackwell) as adopted father figures. The late South African president [Nelson Mandela](/Nelson_Mandela) affectionately referred to her as his "honorary granddaughter." She first met Mandela in 1994 after being invited to South Africa by his party, the [African National Congress](/African_National_Congress), having previously donated proceeds from a photo shoot to the ANC.

In 1993, she was engaged to [U2](/U2) bassist [Adam Clayton](/Adam_Clayton). They had met after Clayton, asked in an interview what he desired but didn't have, replied: "A date with Naomi Campbell." The couple separated the following year. In 1995, she dated [Leonardo DiCaprio](/Leonardo_DiCaprio). From 1998 to 2003, she was in a high-profile, engaged relationship with [Formula One](/Formula_One) team principal [Flavio Briatore](/Flavio_Briatore), whom she now considers a "mentor." From 2008 to 2013, she was with Russian businessman [Vladislav Doronin](/Vladislav_Doronin). Her romantic history also includes relationships with [Robert De Niro](/Robert_De_Niro), [Hassan Jameel](/Hassan_Jameel), [Sean "Diddy" Combs](/Sean_Combs), and [Usher](/Usher_(musician)). In 2019, she was linked to rapper [Skepta](/Skepta).

Campbell's name appears in the contact book and flight logs of the late American financier and convicted sex [trafficker](/Trafficker) [Jeffrey Epstein](/Jeffrey_Epstein). She has also been photographed with Epstein and his associate [Ghislaine Maxwell](/Ghislaine_Maxwell). In August 2019, Campbell addressed the connection on her [YouTube](/YouTube) channel, admitting she knew Epstein through her ex-boyfriend [Flavio Briatore](/Flavio_Briatore). She stated: "What he's done is indefensible... when I heard what he had done, it sickened me to my stomach... I stand with the victims." However, Epstein victim [Virginia Roberts Giuffre](/Virginia_Roberts_Giuffre) has disputed Campbell's claims, alleging that Campbell was a close friend of Maxwell and aware of the situation. In 2022, [The Guardian](/The_Guardian) reported on an alleged 2010 email exchange where Campbell described Maxwell as a "great friend" to Saif Gaddafi. A spokesperson for Campbell stated she did not recognize the exchange and could not verify its authenticity.

In May 2021, she announced the birth of her daughter. In a February 2022 interview with [Vogue](/Vogue_(magazine)), Campbell confirmed her daughter was not adopted. In June 2023, she announced the birth of a son. Campbell later shared that both of her children were born via a surrogate.

#### Campbell v Mirror Group Newspapers Ltd

In 2002, Campbell successfully sued the [Daily Mirror](/Daily_Mirror) for breach of confidentiality after the newspaper published a photograph of her leaving a [Narcotics Anonymous](/Narcotics_Anonymous) meeting. The [High Court](/High_Court_of_Justice) awarded her £3,500 in damages.

#### Testimony for blood diamond case

In August 2010, Campbell was a key witness in the war crimes trial of former Liberian president [Charles Taylor](/Charles_Taylor_(Liberia)). She was called to testify about "[blood diamonds](/Blood_diamonds)" she allegedly received from him in [Cape Town](/Cape_Town), South Africa, in 1997. Campbell testified that two unknown men gave her the uncut stones as a gift, which she assumed were from Taylor. She later gave the diamonds to Jeremy Ractliffe, then the director of the [Nelson Mandela Children's Fund](/Nelson_Mandela_Children%27s_Fund). Ractliffe, suspecting they were illegal, did not donate them but kept them. In August 2010, South African police seized the diamonds from him. Campbell was never charged, as it was determined she lacked criminal intent ([mens rea](/Mens_rea)).

